This paper deals with subgraph similarity search on large probabilistic graph databases, which involves techniques from database systems (cs.DB), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), and information retrieval (cs.IR). The paper also discusses the complexity of the problem, which falls under the scope of computational complexity theory (cs.CC) and theoretical computer science (cs.THE). However, since the focus is on practical solutions and experiments, these categories are less likely.
